## Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

### Context

`common/chat.cpp` hosts a set of **specialized template handlers** — static functions for model families with unique token/tool-call formats that the generic autoparser cannot reliably handle. Each is registered inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` via pattern-matching on the template source string.

The existing Ministral 3 / Magistral Large handler covers Mistral-family templates that use `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]...[/SYSTEM_PROMPT]`. This plan adds a new handler for the simpler **Mistral Instruct v0.3 format**, which wraps user turns in `[INST]/[/INST]`, prepends system messages to the first user turn, and ends assistant turns with `</s>` — without using `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`.

**Constraint:** Only new code is added — no existing handler bodies or `common/chat.h` are modified.

---

### Only file touched: `common/chat.cpp`

---

### Step 1 — New handler function

Inserted **after** `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` (ends ~line 1517), **before** `namespace workaround {` (line 1519):

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v0.3 handler
// Format: system message prepended to first [INST] turn, user wrapped in [INST]/[/INST],
// assistant content followed by </s>.
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt           = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format           = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.preserved_tokens = {
        "[INST]",
        "[/INST]",
    };

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();
    return data;
}
```

The Mistral v0.3 format places no structural tokens around assistant output — the model generates content immediately after `[/INST]`. `p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt)` skips any trailing generation-prompt bytes; `p.content(p.rest())` captures everything else as assistant content.

---

### Step 2 — Detection block in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

Inserted immediately **before** the final `return std::nullopt;` (after the GigaChatV3 block, ~line 1690):

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v0.3 - wraps user turns with [INST]/[/INST], prepends system to first
// user turn, appends </s> after assistant turns.
// Distinguished from Ministral/Magistral Large 3 by absence of [SYSTEM_PROMPT].
// [AVAILABLE_TOOLS] exclusion prevents capturing Nemo-style templates that carry
// their own tool-call format and are correctly handled by the autoparser.
if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```

| Check | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `[INST]` present | Identifies the Mistral `[INST]/[/INST]` family |
| `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent | Distinguishes from Ministral 3 / Mistral v7 (as specified) |
| `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` absent | Excludes Nemo and other tool-capable templates (prevents regression of existing peg_tester tests) |

---

### Nothing else changes

- `common/chat.h` — no new declarations needed; the function is `static`
- `src/llama-chat.h` / `src/llama-chat.cpp` — the older enum-based system is unrelated
- All existing handler function bodies — untouched

---

### Verification

1. The Mistral Nemo template source contains `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]`, so the new check evaluates `false` → Nemo continues through the autoparser → no regression
2. A template with `[INST]` but without `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` or `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` (pure Mistral v0.3) hits the new handler
3. `ctest -R test-chat` should pass unchanged
